{"title_page": "Prince Gyasi", "text_new": "{{short description|Visual Artist}}\n{{Infobox visual artist\n| name          = Prince Gyasi\n| image         = Prince Gyasi.jpg\n| imagesize     = <!-- only needed for images less than 200px and don't mention px -->\n| caption       = Portrait of Prince Gyasi.\n| birth_name    = Prince Gyasi Nyantakyi\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1995|04|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Accra]], [[Ghana]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Ghanaian]]\n| field         = [[Visual Art]], [[Photography]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        =\n| partner       = \n}}\n\n'''Prince Gyasi Nyantakyi''' (born 30 April 1995) also known by the artist name ''Prince Gyasi'' is a Ghanaian international visual artist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.magzter.com/articles/1814/273741/5ac4e7e66c4de|title=The Colour of Hope|website=www.magzter.com|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> He is the co-founder of Boxedkids, a non-profit organization helping kids from [[Accra]],[[Ghana]] get an education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ignant.com/2018/09/04/price-gyasi-photographs-the-colors-faces-and-spirit-of-ghana/|title=Prince Gyasi Photographs The Colors, Faces And Spirit Of Ghana|date=2018-09-04|website=IGNANT|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cheese.konbini.com/saycheesebyorange/a-laide-de-son-telephone-prince-gyasi-documente-avec-talent-la-vie-au-ghana/|title=Avec son t\u00c3\u00a9l\u00c3\u00a9phone, Prince Gyasi documente avec talent le quotidien ghan\u00c3\u00a9en|website=Cheese - The big picture by Konbini|language=fr|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHe had his secondary education at the [[Accra Academy]] senior high school in [[Accra]].\n\n==Career==\n'''Prince''' started taking pictures in 2011 and bought his first [[iPhone]] in 2014 which is the primary tool he uses in creating his art pieces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/news/201901/373087.php|title=Prince Gyasi; Ghanaian Visual Artist Collaborates With Apple To Project Hiplife Genre|last=Online|first=Peace FM|website=peacefmonline.com|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> He began with snapshots of friends, family and models from his hometown of [[Ghana]] and then realized he could seriously use his phone as an arts creation tool, as a means of expression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://livefmghana.com/2019/01/22/hiplife-music-highlighted-in-new-apple-music-project-by-ghanaian-photographer/|title=Hiplife Music highlighted in new Apple Music project by Ghanaian Photographer|date=2019-01-22|website=Live 91.9 FM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\nHe using an [[iPhone]] to shoot is a way to distinguish his art from other visual artists and photographers to break the codes of this singular and elitist art. His work is all about conveying feelings through colors and giving the floor to the people that are left aside from the society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nataal.com/prince-gyasi/|title=Prince Gyasi|website=nataal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> He indeed considers his use of colors as a source of therapy to his audience. Motherhood, Fatherhood, childhood can be considered as his most characteristic themes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodmorningamerica.com/culture/story/black-photographers-reflect-art-tyler-mitchells-history-making-57090573|title=5 black photographers reflect on their art, Vogue's history-making Beyonc\u00e9 cover|last=America|first=Good Morning|website=Good Morning America|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\n===Exhbition===\n'''Prince Gyasi''' was signed to Nil Gallery Paris in 2018 which gave him the chance to exhibit his art pieces at multiple art fairs in the USA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://txcontemporary.com/galleries/nil-gallery-texas-contemporary-2018|title=Nil Gallery - Texas Contemporary 2018|website=Texas Contemporary|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\nHe has exhibited in the Seattle Contemporary Art fair, Texas Contemporary Art Fair,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://afropunk.com/2018/09/control-identity-power-and-resistance/|title=CONTROL: IDENTITY, POWER AND RESISTANCE|date=2018-09-28|website=AFROPUNK|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> Artsy & Context Art Miami and pulse Contemporary Art Fair (Art Basel Miami).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulseartfair.com/exhibitors-pmb18/|title=2018 {{!}} All Exhibitors|website=pulseartfair.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> Prince has also exhibited some of his works at the Investec Capetown Art Fair in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2019/02/14/ghanaian-visual-artist-prince-gyasi-for-investec-cape-town-art-fair-2019/|title=Ghanaian visual artist Prince Gyasi for Investec Cape Town Art Fair 2019|date=2019-02-14|website=Citi Newsroom|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\n===A Great Day In Accra===\nIn December 2018, he got commissioned by [[Apple Inc.]] to work on a project in Ghana titled ''A Great Day In Accra'' to push the Hiplife music genre in Ghana to the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/entertainment/music/sarkodie-obrafour-edem-others-featured-in-apple-musics-hiplife-essentials-playlist/3w7zs08|title=Sarkodie, Obrafour, Edem, others featured in Apple Music\u2019s Hiplife Essentials playlist|date=2019-01-24|website=Entertainment|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> In this project he shot Ghanaian hiplife  musicians like [[Gyedu-Blay Ambolley]], [[Reggie Rockstone]], [[Okyeame Kwame]], Rab Bakari, [[Abrewa Nana]], [[Hammer of The Last Two]], Beat Menace, [[Gurunkz]], [[Joey B]], [[EL (rapper)]], [[DJ Breezy]], Stargo, [[Kirani Ayat]], Akan (Musician), Kiddblack, Ansah Live, Imani N.A.D, Toyboi, [[Kwesi Arthur]] and Shadow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okayafrica.com/prince-gyasi-ghana-hiplife-a-great-day-in-accra-photo-series/|title=Visual Artist Prince Gyasi Gathers Ghana's Hiplife Greats in 'A Great Day In Accra' Photo Series|date=2019-01-23|website=OkayAfrica|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/entertainment/music/reggie-rockstone-kwesi-arthur-joey-b-others-featured-in-apple-musics-new-documentary/cc8kk2x|title=Reggie Rockstone, Kwesi Arthur, Joey B, others featured in Apple Music\u2019s new documentary|date=2019-01-24|website=Entertainment|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==Speaking Engagements==\n===2019 Skoll World Forum===\n'''Prince Gyasi''' was invited on 9 April 2019 to give a speech about his creative works during the 2019 [[Skoll Foundation|Skoll World Forum]] at the [[Oxford University]] in London. During his speech he spoke about the stories behind his work of arts and his influences. He also spoke about his non-profit organization Boxed kids which he co-founded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2019/06/visual-artist-prince-gyasi-speaks-at-2019-skoll-world-forum-at-oxford-university/|title=Visual artist Prince Gyasi speaks at 2019 Skoll World Forum at Oxford University|date=2019-06-18|website=Citi Newsroom|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Mentions==\n*He was mentioned by [[Vanity Fair (magazine)]] as one of the top 9 visual artist to follow in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://enewsgh.com/2019/01/prince-gyasi-the-face-behind-apples-latest-project-a-great-day-in-accra/|title=Prince Gyasi: The face behind Apple's latest project \"A Great Day In Accra\"|date=2019-01-22|website=Proudly Ghanaian! {{!}} EnewsGH|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n*Prince Gyasi was part of five black photographers interviewed by Good Morning America to speak about their work and about Vogue's historic cover with [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goodmorningamerica.com/culture/story/black-photographers-reflect-art-tyler-mitchells-history-making-57090573|title=5 black photographers reflect on their art and Tyler Mitchell's history-making Vogue cover|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n*Prince Gyasi has been featured on the [[BBC]] Africa for his exceptional way of making images with his iPhone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-africa-47585593/prince-gyasi-instagram-photographer-on-capturing-accra-life|title=Accra's Instagram artist on capturing life|website=BBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* Prince has also been featured by [[CNN]] style as one of the seven leading African photographers from across the continent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/african-photographers-nataal-everyday-africa-tokini-peterside/index.html|title=Experts name top African photographers across the continent|first=Ana |last=Rosado|date=2019-04-29|website=CNN Style|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.nilgallery.com/princegyasi Nil Gallery]\n*[https://www.princegyasi.com/ Official Website]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UEkqFvffRSM&feature=youtu.be/ Prince giving a speech at the Skoll Forum]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Ghana topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gyasi, Prince}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Accra Academy]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Visual Artist}}\n{{Infobox visual artist\n| name          = Prince Gyasi\n| image         = Prince Gyasi.jpg\n| imagesize     = <!-- only needed for images less than 200px and don't mention px -->\n| caption       = Portrait of Prince Gyasi.\n| birth_name    = Prince Gyasi Nyantakyi\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1995|04|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Accra]], [[Ghana]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Ghanaian]]\n| field         = [[Visual Art]], [[Photography]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        